  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Global Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n2. Regulatory Coordination\n- Information sharing between national financial intelligence units\n- Harmonization of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Collaborative investigations across jurisdictions\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk jurisdictions\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Extradition agreements\n- Asset freezing and recovery\n- International criminal prosecution\n- Sanctions against non-compliant countries\n\n5. Legal Instruments\n- Bilateral and multilateral agreements\n- Mutual legal assistance protocols\n- Uniform legal definitions of money laundering\n- Standardized reporting mechanisms\n\n6. Financial Institution Obligations\n- International banking compliance standards\n- Mandatory reporting requirements\n- Risk assessment protocols\n- Training and internal control systems\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating international financial crimes.",
